properties.Name: Gemstone
properties.Description: A precious or semiprecious stone that may be used as a jewel when cut and polished.

Columns.Name: GemstoneId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a gemstone.

Columns.Name: GemstoneDescription
Columns.Description: The description of a gemstone.

Columns.Name: PolishDescription
Columns.Description: A description of the measure of smoothness on a diamond's facets.

Columns.Name: LusterDescription
Columns.Description: A description of the sharpness of light reflections from a pearl. This is one of the pearl value factors, and it is a critical component of every pearl's beauty.

Columns.Name: LightReturnDescription
Columns.Description: A description of the total intensity of light reflected by a faceted gem.

Columns.Name: GemstoneSymmetryDescription
Columns.Description: A description regarding the symmetry of the gemstone.

Columns.Name: GemstoneTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a gemstone type.

Columns.Name: GemstoneCaratWeight
Columns.Description:
The gemstone weight in carats.

Note:
"Carat" is a term used for the denoting the weight of gemstones. "Karat" is a term that describes the purity level of gold.

Columns.Name: GemstonePerCaratCostAmount
Columns.Description: The carat weigh multiplied by the carat cost is the total cost of a gemstone.

Columns.Name: NumberOfFacets
Columns.Description:
The number of facets of the gemstone, where facets are the flat surfaces on a cut stone. 

The placement of facets determines how much light reflects through the stone.

Columns.Name: GemstoneLengthMm
Columns.Description:
The length of the gemstone in mm.

MM or mm is the abbreviation for millimeter, the standard unit of measurement for jewelry dimensions.

Columns.Name: GemstoneWidthMm
Columns.Description:
The width of the gemstone in mm.

MM or mm is the abbreviation for millimeter, the standard unit of measurement for jewelry dimensions.

Columns.Name: GemstoneHeightMm
Columns.Description:
The height of the gemstone in mm.

MM or mm is the abbreviation for millimeter, the standard unit of measurement for jewelry dimensions.

Columns.Name: GemstoneDiameterMm
Columns.Description:
The diameter of the gemstone in mm.

MM or mm is the abbreviation for millimeter, the standard unit of measurement for jewelry dimensions.

Columns.Name: GemstoneTopView
Columns.Description: The top view of the gemstone.

Columns.Name: GemstoneLeftView
Columns.Description: The gemstone  left View

Columns.Name: GemstoneRightView
Columns.Description: The gemstone right View

Columns.Name: Gemstone360DegreeView
Columns.Description: The gemstone 360 degree View

Columns.Name: GemstoneMohsHardnessScaleNumber
Columns.Description: The Mohs scale of mineral hardness is based on the ability of one natural sample of mineral to scratch another mineral visibly and ranges from 1-10.

Columns.Name: LaserInscribedGemstoneIndicator
Columns.Description: A diamond can be microscopically inscribed on its girdle with its unique GIA Report Number, a personal message, or any other text, symbols or logos.

Columns.Name: LaserInscribedGemstoneText
Columns.Description: The text of the laser-inscribed gemstone.

Columns.Name: AggregateMaterialIndicator
Columns.Description: A gem material that's composed of small crystals or particles. Chalcedony, jade, lapis lazuli, malachite, and turquoise are aggregates.

Columns.Name: PreciousGemstoneIndicator
Columns.Description:
All gemstones are considered precious since they are all rare and there is a limited supply of them.

The traditional list of gemstones that are considered precious stones are:

- Diamond
- Ruby
- Sapphire
- Emerald

All other gemstones are considered as being

Columns.Name: SemiPreciousGemstoneIndicator
Columns.Description:
All gemstones are considered precious since they are all rare and there is a limited supply of them.

The traditional list of gemstones that are considered precious stones are:

- Diamond
- Ruby
- Sapphire
- Emerald

All other gem

Columns.Name: FacetedGemstoneIndicator
Columns.Description: A faceted gem is a gemstone cut in a manner so that it is covered with small flat polished surfaces. Most transparent gems are faceted.

Columns.Name: ImitationGemstoneIndicator
Columns.Description: An imitation is a gem look-alike. Unlike a synthetic, an imitation (or simulant) doesn't have the same chemistry, structure, or properties as the gem it resembles. Appearance is the only similarity.

Columns.Name: SimulatedGemstoneIndicator
Columns.Description: A simulated gemstone is a man-made stone that resembles the color of a birthstone.

Columns.Name: LabCreatedGemstoneIndicator
Columns.Description: A lab-created gemstone is one produced in a laboratory setting. Lab-created stones have the same chemical, physical and optical properties as natural gemstones.

Columns.Name: SyntheticStoneIndicator
Columns.Description: A synthetic stone is a colored stone produced in a laboratory setting. Synthetic stones have the same chemical, physical and optical properties as natural gemstones. They may also be called lab-created stones.

Columns.Name: LooseGemstoneIndicator
Columns.Description: A loose diamond is one that is sold independently of a ring. It can be purchased in any cut or size.

Columns.Name: DoubletIndicator
Columns.Description: A doublet is an assembled gem made with two main components.

Columns.Name: JewelryProductGemstoneNote
Columns.Description: A note, comment or additional information regarding the jewelry product gemstone.

Columns.Name: GemstoneShapeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a gemstone shape.

Columns.Name: GemstoneSettingTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a gemstone setting type.

Columns.Name: GemstoneConditionId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a gemstone condition.

Columns.Name: GemstoneColorId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a gemstone color.

Columns.Name: GemstoneGradeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a gemstone grade.

Columns.Name: GemstoneClarityRatingId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a gemstone clarity rating.
